<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">September 28, 2023</h2>
<a href="/lit-hub-daily-september-28-2023/"><img class="wp-image-226489 size-thumbnail aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/Alicia-Elliott-e1695845480468-150x150.jpeg" alt="" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://thewalrus.ca/alicia-elliott-and-then-she-fell/" class="external" target="_blank">Alicia Elliott and Scaachi Koul</a> in conversation.</li>
 	<li>Apparently, <a href="https://www.newscientist.com/article/2394538-having-books-in-your-zoom-background-makes-you-seem-more-trustworthy/" class="external" target="_blank">having books in your Zoom background makes you look more trustworthy</a>.</li>
 	<li>Katie Kadue on <a href="https://publicdomainreview.org/essay/free-speech-and-bad-meats/" class="external" target="_blank">Milton’s debt to early modern housewives</a>.</li>
</ul>
<a title="LitHub Daily: May 1, 2015" href="/lit-hub-daily-september-28-2023/"><button>More News</button></a></li>
	    			</ul>
